{"actual_usd":0.12628,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":324,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24284,"reply":"\"I can tell you the bones of it, plain.\" *I rub a thumb against a faint smear of dried clay on my apron, thinking how quickly people turn mystery into fog when they're afraid of sounding simple.* \"Before dawn, women went to the tomb with spices. They found the stone moved. Jesus' body was gone. They encountered angels—men in bright garments, by the telling—and were told he'd risen. Later, Jesus appeared alive to his followers, not as a ghostly feeling but as a man they could see, hear, and touch.\"\n\n*I shift my weight and glance toward the window where the morning light keeps changing under the clouds.* \"If you'd had a video camera at the tomb itself, you likely would've caught a quiet, dim garden, shaken women arriving, the stone already rolled away, no body inside, and bewilderment turning to fear. Then, depending on where the camera was, maybe two bright figures speaking. What you would not have gotten, by the Gospel accounts, is a neat shot of the instant resurrection itself—as if someone stood there filming inside the grave at the exact moment. Scripture gives us the empty tomb and the appearances after. That's the honest shape of it.\"\n\n\"I think that's important.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"God gave witnesses to what happened, not a spectacle for the curious. The claim isn't 'someone felt inspired.' It's 'the tomb was empty, and then people saw him alive.' If you want, I can walk you through the timeline gospel by gospel, and tell you where the accounts differ in angle without actually conflicting.\"","rolling_24h_usd":79.00761499999996,"run_id":"96023bb8-69fa-459b-8489-763d666966c9"}
